=begin pod

=head1 NAME

LLM::Classifiers::Emotions - 28-way text emotion classifier using Cohee's
quantized DistilBERT go-emotions model

=head1 SYNOPSIS

=begin code :lang<raku>

use LLM::Classifiers::Emotions;

my $clf = LLM::Classifiers::Emotions::Classifier.new;

say $clf.top("I'm so angry I could scream");
    # 'anger'

say $clf.top("I'm really curious how this works");
    # 'curiosity'

for $clf.classify("I love you more than anything")[^3] -> %r {
    say "{ %r<label> }: { %r<score>.fmt('%.3f') }";
}
    # love: 0.263
    # caring: 0.175
    # admiration: 0.116

=end code

=head1 STATUS

v0.1 — single-text inference only. Batch / multi-label modes are
deferred to later releases. See LIMITATIONS below.

Output is fully deterministic under the CPU execution provider —
bit-identical logits across runs for the same input on the same
ONNX Runtime version. Tests assert this invariant.

=head1 INSTALLATION

=begin code :lang<shell>

zef install LLM::Classifiers::Emotions

=end code

At install time, C<Build.rakumod> downloads three files
(tokenizer.json, config.json, and a 68 MB quantized ONNX model)
from the module's GitHub Release, verifies SHA256 against bundled
checksums, and stages them under C<$XDG_DATA_HOME/
LLM-Classifiers-Emotions/>. If the GitHub Release path fails (or
if you set C<LLM_EMOTIONS_FROM_HF=1>), it falls back to downloading
directly from Cohee's HuggingFace repo at a pinned revision via
C<HuggingFace::API>.

No system-wide changes are made. C<zef uninstall> leaves the staged
model alone — remove it manually if you want the ~70 MB back.

=head2 Environment variables

=begin table
LLM_EMOTIONS_BINARY_URL   | Override GitHub Release base URL
LLM_EMOTIONS_BINARY_ONLY=1 | Refuse HF fallback; fail if the primary path doesn't complete
LLM_EMOTIONS_FROM_HF=1    | Skip primary, go straight to HuggingFace (dev / debug)
LLM_EMOTIONS_CACHE_DIR    | Override download cache dir (default $XDG_CACHE_HOME)
LLM_EMOTIONS_DATA_DIR     | Override staged base dir (default $XDG_DATA_HOME)
LLM_EMOTIONS_MODEL_DIR    | (runtime) load model from this dir instead of the staged dir
=end table

=head1 API

=head2 LLM::Classifiers::Emotions::Classifier

=head3 new(:@providers = [CPU], :$model-dir = IO::Path, :$log-id = 'llm-emotions')

Load the tokenizer, model, and label map. C<@providers> is passed
through to C<ONNX::Native::Session>; defaults to CPU-only so output
is reproducible. C<$model-dir> overrides the XDG-staged lookup —
useful for dev iteration or pointing at an alternate go-emotions
variant.

Throws C<X::LLM::Classifiers::Emotions::ModelMissing> if the staged
dir isn't found and no override is supplied. Throws
C<X::LLM::Classifiers::Emotions::InvalidConfig> if C<config.json>
doesn't parse.

=head3 classify(Str:D $text --> List[Hash])

Classify one text. Returns a list of 28 Hash entries, sorted
descending by score, each with C<< label => Str >> and
C<< score => Num >>. Scores sum to 1.0 ± 1e-5 (softmax invariant).

Input longer than 512 tokens is truncated — DistilBERT's positional
embeddings are fixed at that length, and Cohee's tokenizer doesn't
truncate on its own.

=head3 top(Str:D $text, Numeric :$min-score --> Str)

Argmax label — the most-likely single emotion. With C<:$min-score>,
returns C<Str> (the type object / undefined) if the top score falls
below the threshold.

=head3 labels(--> List[Str])

The 28 go-emotions labels in id order:
C<admiration amusement anger annoyance approval caring confusion
curiosity desire disappointment disapproval disgust embarrassment
excitement fear gratitude grief joy love nervousness optimism pride
realization relief remorse sadness surprise neutral>.

=head3 raw-logits(Str:D $text --> List[Num])

Pre-softmax 28-element logit list, straight from the ONNX session.
Exposed for tests that want to assert bit-identical output as a
determinism check. Normal callers should use C<classify>.

=head3 dispose() / DESTROY

Release the underlying ONNX session. Idempotent.

=head1 MODEL

=begin item
B<Source:> C<Cohee/distilbert-base-uncased-go-emotions-onnx> on
HuggingFace
(L<https://huggingface.co/Cohee/distilbert-base-uncased-go-emotions-onnx>).
The same model SillyTavern uses for its "expressions" feature.
=end item

=begin item
B<Architecture:> DistilBERT-base-uncased (6 transformer layers, 66 M
parameters), fine-tuned for sequence classification on the
GoEmotions dataset.
=end item

=begin item
B<Quantization:> int8 dynamic quantization. ~68 MB on disk vs.
~268 MB for the full-precision variant. Trivial accuracy difference
for this task.
=end item

=begin item
B<Training data:> L<GoEmotions|https://aclanthology.org/2020.acl-main.372/>
(Demszky et al, 2020) — ~58k English Reddit comments labelled for
27 emotion categories + "neutral".
=end item

=begin item
B<Revision pin:> C<d22488bc83be87678f12eee8a3f65a65de94ef85>. The
C<BINARY_TAG> file at the dist root and C<resources/REVISION>
together pin the exact model weights shipped by this release.
Bump both together when updating.
=end item

=head1 DETERMINISM

Under the default CPU provider, ONNX Runtime uses MLAS (Microsoft's
matrix math library) for the inference hot path. MLAS is fully
deterministic across runs for the same input + same ORT version:
logits are bit-identical, softmax preserves that, and argmax is
stable.

B<CoreML divergence note:> if you pass C<:providers<coreml cpu>>
on macOS, CoreML may produce slightly different scores (at the
~1e-3 level) because some ops downcast to fp16 internally on the
Neural Engine. The I<argmax> label still agrees with CPU for
go-emotions across all inputs we've tested. Tests pin C<:cpu> so
they pass regardless of provider.

Upgrading ONNX Runtime (the C<ONNX::Native> BINARY_TAG) may shift
logits at the LSB level if MLAS gets a new kernel. Re-compute test
expectations after such an upgrade.

=head1 PLATFORM NOTES

=head2 macOS

Staged under C<~/.local/share/LLM-Classifiers-Emotions/>. First
load of the model is ~200ms on Apple Silicon; subsequent classify
calls are ~30ms for typical chat-length input.

=head2 Linux

Same staging path. Performance is comparable on contemporary x86_64
(MLAS's AVX2 kernels kick in), slightly slower on aarch64.

=head2 Windows

Not supported in v0.1 — C<ONNX::Native> itself doesn't ship Windows
binaries yet. Once that lands, this module should work without
change (the protocols and file formats are platform-neutral).

=head1 LIMITATIONS

=item Single-text inference only — no batch mode. Classifying
      thousands of strings takes thousands of session runs.
      Batching is a worthwhile ~2x speedup and is queued for v0.2.
=item Single-label output only. The underlying GoEmotions dataset
      permits multi-label annotations; this module's argmax discards
      that information.
=item Input beyond 512 tokens is silently truncated. Callers that
      care about long-document sentiment should summarise or chunk
      upstream.
=item English-only. GoEmotions is entirely English Reddit; the
      model has no non-English training signal and scores garbage
      on non-English input.
=item Training-set biases — Reddit 2020 comments skew US-centric,
      young, male, and more casual than written text generally.
      Performance on formal text or non-Reddit dialects is
      degraded.

